  rdfs:label """In conversation, it is useful to combine tenses when giving an answer to develop the
  conversation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361961Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25589-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Adjectives that come before the noun fit into five categories: BRAGS (Beauty, Rank,
  Age, Good/bad and Size/quantity)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361965Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25589-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Adverbs that describe adjectives usually precede them."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361971Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25589-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Adverbs that modify the verb and adverbs of frequency usually come after the
  verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361975Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25589-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Extend answers by using a variety of subjects, adding a different time frame and
  using an element of contrast."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361979Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29157-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Use the PALM acronym to structure photo descriptions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.361997Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29157-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The BORDER acronym is a useful tool to respond fully and accurately to bullet point
  writing prompts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.362001Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29157-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to carefully check verb endings and adjectival agreement when
  translating from English to French."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.362005Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25603-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a broad vocabulary to be successful at answering listening
  comprehension questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.362250Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25603-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to listen out for synonyms and distractors when answering listening
  comprehension questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.362254Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21674-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Comparative and superlative adjectives can be used to enhance opinions and
  descriptions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.363216Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21674-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to consider word order when translating texts containing
  superlatives."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.363220Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21674-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Carefully planning, rehearsing and immediately repeating a speaking task helps to
  improve performance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.363224Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21674-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Creating a checklist for range of language and another for accuracy can enhance the
  quality of extended writing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.363228Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21634-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Many adjectives come after the noun in French."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364046Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21634-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Adjectives that come before the noun fit into five categories: BRAGS (Beauty, Rank,
  Age, Good/Bad and Size/quantity)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364052Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21634-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some -ir verbs in the present follow the pattern of venir. The stem is vien(n) in
  all but the nous and vous forms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364056Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21634-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """[ien] is pronounced like 'bien'. [e] can be lengthened to sound like [ê/è] in the
  ils/elles forms of verbs like venir."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364060Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21634-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Pour + infinitive can be used to give reasons."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364064Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25557-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To talk about what you can, know, have to, or want to do, use modal verbs:
  'pouvoir', 'savoir', 'devoir', 'vouloir'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364507Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25557-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Modal verbs are usually followed by an infinitive."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364511Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25557-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """[-ill-/-ille] is pronounced as in 'fille', [-aill-/-ail] is pronounced as in
  'taille'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364515Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21632-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some -re verbs in the present tense follow the pattern of 'traduire' (-s added to
  stem for 'nous/vous/ils/elles' forms)"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364820Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21632-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[s] is pronounced as in 'maison' when between two vowels."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364824Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21632-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The verb 'écrire' and its derivatives are conjugated differently (-v added to stem
  in 'nous/vous/ils/elles' forms)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364828Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21632-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Four groups of -re verbs are verbs like 'entendre', verbs like 'prendre', verbs like
  'traduire' and verbs like 'écrire'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364832Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21632-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All four groups of -re verbs can be combined with -er verbs to describe somebody's
  interests and achievements."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.364836Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21638-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Words ending in a consonant + -le(s) or consonant + -re(s) stress the vowel before
  the consonant, e.g., 'terrible'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.365934Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21638-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'à' + definite article combine to make au/à la/à l’ or aux, depending on the gender,
  quantity and spelling of the noun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.365938Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21638-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'à' can be translated as 'at', 'to', 'in' and 'on' depending on its place and use in
  the sentence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.365942Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21638-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Conflict and independence movements in Algeria and Senegal shaped their identities
  and relations with France."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.365946Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21659-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Direct and indirect object pronouns precede both parts of the verb (auxiliary and
  past participle) in the perfect tense."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.366798Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21659-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Direct and indirect object pronouns can be usefully combined to create complex
  texts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.366802Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21659-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to plan both the ideas and language needed and to think about
  structure when writing a longer text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.366806Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21659-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to create a checklist both for range of language and for accuracy
  when creating a longer text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.366810Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25558-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Three common irregular verbs and their past participles are: avoir (eu), faire
  (fait), boire (bu)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.368647Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25558-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """[u] is pronounced as in 'tu'. Many past participles end in 'u' and rhyme with each
  other."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.368651Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25558-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The past participles of the four modal verbs are: dû, pu, voulu, and su."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.368655Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25558-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Modal verbs in the perfect tense use 'avoir' as the auxiliary verb."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.368659Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25524-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use un/une (indefinite article) to describe whole things, and du/de la/de l'
  (partitive article) for parts of things."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.386362Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25524-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Uncountable nouns, such as water or money, do not have a plural form. They are used
  with the partitive article."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.386366Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25524-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'Y' can replace 'à' + [a place] to mean 'there', e.g. 'elle y va demain'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.386370Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25524-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'En' can replace 'de' + noun and can mean '(of) it/them', e.g. 'j'aime la confiture,
  j'en mange tous les jours'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.386373Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25524-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[en] is pronounced as in ‘enfant’."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.386377Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21668-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Moi-même', 'toi-même', etc. emphasise a person's involvement in an action and are
  translated as myself, yourself, etc."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.392991Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21668-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to plan the ideas, the vocabulary and the grammar to be included
  when writing a longer text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.392995Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21668-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Careful planning of a speaking task, pre-rehearsal and immediate repetition of the
  task all improve performance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.392999Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21668-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When developing a personal response, it's helpful to use a dictionary to look up new
  vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.393003Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21688-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When the relative pronoun relates to the object of the sentence, we use 'que'
  instead of 'qui'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.393378Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21688-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Où and quand can also be used in relative clauses to detail where or when something
  happens."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.393382Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21688-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """[qu] sounds like 'question' or 'quatre', [en/an] sound like 'enfant' and [e] sounds
  like 'je'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.393385Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21688-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Dont is another relative pronoun; it means 'of which' or 'whose'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.393392Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21669-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To make an adjective feminine we can: add -e, -x to -se, -el to -elle, -en to -enne,
  -f to -ve, -er to ère."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.394248Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21669-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If an adjective ends in mute -e, there is no change to form the feminine e.g.
  'triste'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.394254Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21669-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form plural adjectives we add an -s, unless the adjective ends in -x or -s. -al
  and -eau change to -aux and -eaux."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.394259Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21669-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """[è] sounds like 'tête', important when pronouncing feminine agreements of adjectives
  ending in -er: 'entier', 'entière'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.394263Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21673-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some comparative adjective forms are irregular: 'bon' becomes 'meilleur' (better)
  and 'mauvais' becomes 'pire' (worse)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.399417Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21673-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some superlative forms are irregular: le/la/les + meilleur(e) (s)= the best;
  le/la/les + pire(s)= the worst"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.399421Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21673-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[oi] sounds like 'voir', [au] sounds like 'gauche', [u] sounds like 'tu'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.399425Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25556-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Using the perfect tense and imperfect tense together enables us to express ongoing
  and isolated events in the past."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.401310Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25556-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Using qui, que, où and quand in relative clauses provides more information and adds
  complexity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.401314Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25556-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Using a range of negative structures adds subtlety and complexity to descriptions
  and opinions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.401320Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25556-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Combining different tenses allows students to give a more developed answers to
  conversation questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.401324Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25579-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Direct object pronouns are: 'me', 'te', 'le'/'la'/'l'', 'nous', 'vous' and 'les'.
  They precede the verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.405281Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25579-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Indirect object pronouns are: 'me', 'te', 'lui', 'nous', 'vous' and 'leur'. They
  precede the verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.405285Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25579-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Moi', 'toi', 'lui', 'elle', 'nous', 'vous', 'eux', 'elles' are used as emphatic
  pronouns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.405289Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27637-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Listening and reading texts can be exploited to enrich our topic-specific
  vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406316Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27637-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Account for every word when translating from French, but remember there might be a
  different number of words in English"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406320Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27637-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In role-play keep answers short and focus on accurately conveying meaning to cover
  each bullet point."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.406324Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25553-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Reflexive pronouns enable us to express an action done to oneself or two or more
  subjects acting upon one another."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.407874Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25553-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Infinitives of reflexive verbs are always preceded by se or s’. Choose the correct
  pronoun when conjugating the verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.407878Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25553-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The negative component 'ne' goes before the reflexive pronoun. 'Pas' goes after the
  verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.407882Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25553-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Extend answers by giving and justifying opinions and using a variety of adjectives,
  adverbs, pronouns and intensifiers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.407886Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25552-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The verb spellings of regular reflexive verbs are the same as regular -er, -ir and
  -re verbs in the present tense."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.414015Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25552-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Some verbs have a secondary meaning that uses a reflexive pronoun."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.414019Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25552-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some verbs use reflexive pronouns in French when their English translation doesn't
  include a reflexive idea."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.414023Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25552-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Sometimes the reflexive pronoun indicates the action is exchanged between two or
  more subjects acting upon one another."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.414027Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21676-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To describe an action as the best, the most or the least, we use superlatives: le +
  plus/moins + adverb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.420160Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21676-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The superlative adverb goes directly after the verb: il parle le plus lentement."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.420164Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21676-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Irregular superlative form 'le mieux' is used for 'the best' when describing
  a verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.420168Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21676-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Two superlative forms 'le plus mal' and 'le moins bien' are used for 'the worst'
  when describing a verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.420175Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29152-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ordinal numbers are created by (removing -e and) adding -ième to a number:
  'deuxième', 'onzième'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.422660Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29152-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """in- or im- can be added to adjectives, adverbs or nouns to give the opposite
  meaning. English equivalent is un- or in-."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.422667Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29152-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """-ion or -ation can be added to the verb stem to form a noun where the English
  equivalent is -ion or -ation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.422671Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29152-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Agent nouns can be created by adding -eur or -ateur to the verb stem, e.g.
  'consommer' - 'consommateur'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.422675Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27602-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Using a range of negative structures adds subtlety and complexity to descriptions
  and viewpoints."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.423502Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27602-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Indefinite adjectives are used to describe a noun and give more detail. They go
  before the noun they describe."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.423506Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27602-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When approaching extended writing tasks, dividing each bullet point into two
  paragraphs can be helpful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.423512Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25590-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ordinal numbers are created by (removing -e and) adding -ième to a number:
  'deuxième', 'onzième'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427308Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25590-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """in- or im- can be added to adjectives, adverbs or nouns to give the opposite
  meaning. English equivalent is un- or in-."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427314Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25590-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """-ion or -ation can be added to the verb stem to form a noun where the English
  equivalent is -ion or -ation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427319Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25590-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Agent nouns can be created by adding -eur or -ateur to the verb stem, e.g.
  'consommer' - 'consommateur'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.427323Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25526-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """French cuisine is celebrated for its wide array of dishes and foods, many of which
  are famous around the world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.431893Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25526-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'y' and 'en' are often used in speech to replace a group of other words."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.431898Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25526-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Y means 'there' or '(to, about, in) it'. En means '(of) it/them'. When used
  together, 'y' comes before 'en'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.431902Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25526-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In formal role-plays, it is important to be able to understand formal speech,
  including 'vous' verbs and 'votre'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.431906Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21724-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Using a range of negative structures with a range of tenses adds strength and
  subtlety to your points."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.432784Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21724-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Take care when translating negatives into English. Consider word order carefully. Ne
  ...que is not negative in English."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.432788Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21724-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to plan both the ideas and language needed and to think about
  structure when writing a longer text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.432792Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21724-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to create a checklist both for range of language and for accuracy
  when creating a longer text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.432797Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21633-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Adjectives often change their spelling for feminine and plural forms. Those ending
  in -e do not change in the feminine."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587819Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21633-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Adjectives beau, nouveau and vieux have feminine forms: belle, nouvelle and vieille.
  Beau and nouveau add -x in plural."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587825Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21633-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many -ir verbs in the present follow the pattern of choisir: remove -ir and add -is,
  -is, -it, -issons, -issez, -issent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587830Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21633-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many -ir verbs follow the pattern of 'partir': remove -(t)ir and add: -s, -s, -t,
  -ons, -ez, -ent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587835Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21633-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The sounds [i] like 'midi', [s/ss] like 'saucisse' and [r] like 'rue' are common in
  verbs like 'choisir' and 'partir'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.587839Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21718-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is useful to practise recalling present, aller + infinitive, then simple future
  e.g. je suis, je vais être, je serai."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.589274Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21718-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to include regular and common irregular simple future verbs when
  writing about future plans."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.589278Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21718-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Wherever possible in your writing, it is good to demonstrate that you can move
  between different tenses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.589282Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21672-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To make comparisons in French we use plus ...que, moins ...que and aussi ...que with
  adjectives and adverbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.592486Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21672-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To describe something as the best, the most or the least, we use superlatives:
  le/la/les + plus/moins + adjective."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.592490Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21672-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """[qu] sounds like 'quatre'. There is no sound equivalent to the 'qu' sound in
  English."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.592494Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25525-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[y] sounds like 'y' in 'physique'"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.592501Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25525-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Y can replace the object of a verb followed by à  e.g. elle y a pensé."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.592505Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25525-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "We do not use 'y' for people. We use pronouns in this case e.g. Je pense à lui."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.592509Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25525-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Il y en a means 'there is/are some'. It can also be used in the past tense: il y en
  avait and the future: il y en aura."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.592514Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21675-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To make comparisons in French we use plus... que, moins... que and aussi... que with
  adjectives and adverbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594412Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21675-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Some comparative adverb forms are irregular: 'bien' becomes 'mieux' (better)"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594416Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21675-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'Mal' becomes 'moins bien' / 'plus mal' (worse)"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594421Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21675-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[i] sounds like 'midi' and [eu] sounds like 'deux'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594425Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25565-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The passive voice places the emphasis on the person or thing affected by the
  action."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594431Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25565-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The passive can be used to add style, clarity or emphasis in everyday and formal
  written French."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594435Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25565-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Using regular and irregular past participles in active and passive sentences adds
  variety and complexity to your work."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594439Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25565-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When developing a personal response, it is helpful to use reference materials to
  look up new vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594446Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25584-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Yes/no questions in all tenses are formed by inversion of subject and verb, adding
  'est-ce que' or using intonation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594551Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25584-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To ask questions using question words, add a question word before the inverted verb
  or before 'est-ce que'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594556Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25584-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Being able to ask questions in different tenses, as well as answer them, is key to
  successful communication."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594560Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21711-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[r] sounds like 'rue' and [a] sounds like 'animal'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594582Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21711-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Aller + infinitive is a 2-verb structure to express what is going to happen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594587Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21711-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The simple future in French is a 1-verb future tense meaning will + verb. It's
  'simple' as it's formed with one word."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594593Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21711-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We conjugate the future tense of -er verbs for je, tu, il/elle/on by adding the
  endings -ai, -as, -a to the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594597Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25546-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Time markers and conjunctions, combined with different verb tenses, help a reader to
  follow a text more easily."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594602Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25546-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Include a range of verbs in future and conditional when describing future plans and
  wishes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594606Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25546-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The conditional can be used to compare real and ideal situations."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594610Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25544-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[i] is pronounced as in 'midi', [on] as in 'non', and [ez] as in 'nez'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594635Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25544-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Conjugate the future tense of -er verbs by adding the endings -ai, -as, -a, -ons,
  -ez, -ont to the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594639Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25544-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The conditional has the same stem as the future tense (the infinitive)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594643Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25544-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The conditional endings are: -ais, -ais, -ait, -ions, -iez, -aient. These are the
  same as the imperfect."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594647Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21716-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The present tense forms of 'aller' and 'faire' are highly irregular and must be
  learnt."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594959Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21716-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """French has just one present tense. Time adverbs differentiate between habitual (I
  do) and ongoing (I am doing) actions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594963Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21716-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[i] sounds like 'midi' and [e] sounds like 'je'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594967Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21716-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The simple future stem for the verb 'aller' is 'ir-'. Regular future endings are
  added to this stem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594972Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21716-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The simple future stem for the verb 'faire' is 'fer-'. Regular future endings are
  added to this stem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.594976Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25527-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Montreal is the largest city in the province of Quebec in Canada. It is a bilingual
  city."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.595004Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25527-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When giving directions or instructions to a stranger, use the formal imperative
  'vous' form."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.595008Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25527-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[oi] sounds like 'trois' and [oy] sounds like 'envoyer'"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.595014Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25527-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """‘Être’ is irregular in the imperative. The 'tu' form is 'sois' and the 'vous' form
  is 'soyez'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.595019Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21720-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Aller' + infinitive is used to say 'going to do', and the simple future is used to
  say 'will do'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.595799Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21720-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Ne … plus' is a negative structure which means 'no longer' or 'not anymore', e.g.
  'mon grand-père ne travaille plus'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.595804Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21720-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "When 'plus' is used in a negative sentence, we do not usually hear the 's'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.595808Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21720-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Ne … pas encore' means 'not yet' and is used with the perfect tense, e.g. 'je n'ai
  pas encore fait du ski'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.595812Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21709-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Nous and vous are the emphatic pronouns for us and you (plural/formal)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.595816Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21709-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Emphatic pronouns often follow prepositions, e.g. pour nous, avant vous."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.595820Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21709-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When a nasal vowel such as [an] is followed by a vowel, it is no longer a nasal
  sound but an oral vowel, e.g. ami."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.595825Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21709-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Extended listening and reading texts can be exploited to enrich our vocabulary and
  use of complex structures."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.595829Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21660-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The simple past is formed by combining an auxiliary verb (avoir or être) with a past
  participle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.596676Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21660-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The present perfect is formed in the same way as the simple past, combining an
  auxiliary verb and a past participle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.596680Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21660-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When translating into English, we need to think whether the simple past or the
  present perfect is the best translation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.596684Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25543-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The future and the conditional can be usefully combined to express plans and hopes
  for the future."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597466Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25543-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """For the longer written task, it's important to write about both bullet points and
  develop ideas as much as possible."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597470Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25543-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The BORDER acronym is a useful tool to respond fully and accurately to bullet point
  writing prompts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597475Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21710-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The present tense of 'aller' + infinitive means 'going to' + infinitive and
  describes future actions and events."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597502Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21710-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Negation is two elements, e.g. 'ne … pas' or 'ne ... jamais', going around the main
  verb to express a negative meaning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597506Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21710-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To negate future ideas, put 'ne … pas' around the conjugated part of 'aller',
  followed by the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597510Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25516-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[a] sounds like 'animal' and [au] sounds like 'gauche'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597514Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25516-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Use 'en' to mean 'to' or 'in' for feminine countries or regions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597519Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25516-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use 'à' plus the definite article for 'to' or 'in' masculine countries. 'À' combines
  with 'le'/'les' to form 'au'/'aux'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597523Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25516-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Use 'à' to mean 'to' or 'in' before all cities and towns."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.597527Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21713-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use part of the verb 'aller' plus an infinitive to express going to do e.g. Elles
  vont visiter Paris."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.599527Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21713-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Conjugate the simple future of -er verbs for nous, vous, ils/elles by adding the
  endings -ons, -ez, -ont to infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.599531Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21713-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are many popular cultural events in France each year, such as the 'marche des
  fiertés' in Paris."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.599535Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21719-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use 'ne ... pas' for saying what doesn't happen, 'ne ... jamais' for 'never' and 'ne
  ... rien' for 'nothing'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.599539Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21719-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Wrap 'ne ... pas', 'ne ... jamais' or 'ne ... rien' around the conjugated verb to
  make the sentence negative."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.599545Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21719-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """With 'aller' + infinitive, the negative words wrap around the conjugated form of
  'aller'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.599550Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21656-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Ne ... pas', 'ne ... rien', and 'ne ... jamais' all wrap around the auxiliary verb
  in the perfect tense."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.599554Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21656-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Ne ... personne' is different to other negatives in the past tense. 'Personne'
  comes after the past participle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.599558Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21656-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Present and perfect tenses can be usefully combined to talk about sporting
  personalities, achievements and events."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.599562Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25586-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'Il est', 'il fait', 'il y a' and 'il faut' are common impersonal verbs."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.600130Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25586-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Impersonal verbs 'il vaut mieux' (it's better) and 'ça vaut la peine de' (it's
  worth) are followed by the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.600134Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25586-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To talk about what you can, know, have to, or want to do, use modal verbs:
  'pouvoir', 'savoir', 'devoir', 'vouloir'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.600138Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25586-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "If modal verbs are followed by another verb it must be in the infinitive form."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.600142Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25586-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The past participles of the four modal verbs are: 'dû', 'pu', 'voulu' and 'su'. They
  are used with 'avoir'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.600148Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21680-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Modal verbs and the conditional with vouloir are helpful for describing work tasks
  and future career hopes and plans."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.600152Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21680-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The conditional with vouloir can be used to personalise your writing and
  speaking."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.600156Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21680-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Creating a checklist for range of language and another for accuracy can enhance the
  quality of extended writing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.600160Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21680-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When developing a personal response it's helpful to use reference materials to look
  up new vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.600164Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21707-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Moi', 'toi', 'lui', 'elle', 'eux', and 'elles' mean 'me', 'you', 'him', 'her', and
  'them' as emphatic pronouns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.600726Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21707-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Emphatic pronouns can also be used after a comparative, e.g. 'il est plus sérieux
  que toi'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.600730Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21707-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Planning a speaking task answer carefully, pre-rehearsal and immediate repetition of
  the task improve performance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.600734Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25511-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Moi', 'toi', 'lui', 'elle', 'nous', 'vous', 'eux', elles mean me, you, him, her,
  us, you and them as emphatic pronouns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.601341Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25511-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to plan both the ideas and language needed and to think about
  structure when writing a longer text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.601346Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21715-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use part of the verb 'aller' plus an infinitive to express going to do e.g. Elles
  vont visiter Paris."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602366Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21715-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Conjugate the simple future of -er verbs by adding the correct ending to the
  infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602371Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21715-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use 'aller + infinitive' and the simple future to speak and write about planned
  visits to cultural events."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602375Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21715-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use PALM when describing a photo and BORDER when planning extended pieces of
  writing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602379Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21712-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Aller' + infinitive describes what is going to happen; it tends to be used in more
  informal conversation and writing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602383Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21712-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The simple future expresses what will happen; it tends to be used in more formal
  contexts for predictions or promises."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602387Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21712-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Most consonants at the end of words are silent, e.g. 'tu mangeras'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602391Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21712-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is helpful to practise verb manipulation, e.g. 'jouer', 'je joue', 'je vais
  jouer', 'je jouerai'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602396Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21721-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Negation in French is two elements e.g. ne … pas around the main verb expressing
  negative meaning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602400Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21721-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """With ne … pas, ne … jamais and ne … rien in the past, put auxiliary verb (avoir or
  être) between ne and pas/jamais/rien."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602406Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21721-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """‘Un’, ‘une’, ‘du’, ‘de la’ and ‘des’ change to ‘de’ after a negative e.g. Je ne
  mange pas de viande."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602411Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21721-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In formal speech, liaison can often be heard after negative structures ne … pas, ne
  … plus, and ne … jamais."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602415Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21721-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Using a range of negative structures with a range of tenses adds complexity to your
  writing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602420Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21706-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[ui] sounds like 'huit' and [eu] sounds like 'deux'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602424Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21706-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Emphatic pronouns can be used for emphasis of the subject, e.g. 'Moi, j'adore le
  chocolat !'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602430Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21706-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Other emphatic pronouns are 'lui' ('him'), 'elle' ('her'), 'eux' ('them') and
  'elles' ('them')."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602437Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21706-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Emphatic pronouns are used with 'à' to express possession, e.g. 'Il est à toi, ce
  cahier ?'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602441Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21705-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Emphatic pronouns are often used after prepositions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602867Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21705-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Emphatic pronouns include 'moi' ('me') and 'toi' ('you'). They apply only to people,
  not things."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602872Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21705-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Sans' (without), 'pour' (for), 'avant' (before) and 'chez' (at the house/place of)
  are followed by emphatic pronouns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602876Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21705-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[an] sounds like 'enfant' and [oi] sounds like 'voir'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602880Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21703-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The imperfect tense is used to describe how something or someone 'used to' be and
  what regularly happened in the past."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602884Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21703-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'il y avait' is the imperfect tense form of 'il y a', and means 'there used
  to be'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602888Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21703-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When a word ending in a normally silent consonant is followed by a mute 'h', the
  consonant is heard in liaison."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602892Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21714-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Conjugate the future tense of -er verbs by adding the endings -ai, -as, -a, -ons,
  -ez, -ont to the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602899Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21714-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is helpful to practise spoken recall of present, aller + infinitive, and simple
  future, as part of a 'verb workout'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602903Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21714-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In French the stress or emphasis usually falls on the last syllable of a word or
  phrase."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.602907Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21666-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are 4 ways to turn a masculine noun into a feminine noun: add an e, change
  article, -n to -nne, -eur to -rice."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.603298Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21666-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If a masculine noun ends in -e, there's no change for feminine; if it ends in -s or
  -x, there's no change for plural."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.603303Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21666-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We usually make nouns plural by adding -s. Nouns ending in -eu, -(e)au, -al, or -ail
  make their plurals with -x."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.603307Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21666-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """[ien] sounds like 'bien', [eu/oeu] sounds like 'coeur', [eu] sounds like 'deux' and
  [au] sounds like 'gauche'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.603311Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25541-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The 1-verb future is the equivalent of 'will' + verb. It is formulated with one
  word."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.603315Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25541-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Form the 1-verb future of -er verbs for je, tu, il/elle/on by adding the endings
  -ai, -as, -a to the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.603319Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25541-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The verb vouloir can be used in the conditional to express a wish. It can be
  followed by a noun or an infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.603324Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25541-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The 1st, 2nd, 3rd person forms of vouloir in the conditional all sound the same: je
  voudrais, tu voudrais, il voudrait."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.603330Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25547-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The 1-verb future tense expresses what will happen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.604278Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25547-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The 1-verb future stem for 'être' is 'ser-' and for 'avoir' is 'aur-' Regular future
  endings are added to these stems."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.604282Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25547-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The 1-verb future stem for faire is 'fer-' and for 'aller' is 'ir-' Regular future
  endings are added to these stems."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.604286Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21708-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Nasal vowel sounds occur when one or more vowels precede a nasal consonant e.g. an,
  am, ain, on, en."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.604291Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21708-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The emphatic pronouns 'nous' and 'vous' are used for 'us' and 'you'
  (plural/formal)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.604295Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21708-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """sans (without), pour (for), avant (before) and chez (at the house/place of) are all
  followed by emphatic pronouns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.604299Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25534-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Present participle adjectives can usefully be combined with other adjectives to give
  more information about nouns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.605160Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25534-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Comparative and superlative adjectives can be used to enhance opinions and
  descriptions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.605165Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25534-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to communicate accurately but also to include varied and complex
  language."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.605169Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25534-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When developing a personal response it is helpful to use reference materials to look
  up new vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.605173Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21702-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'avoir' and 'faire' have regular stems in the imperfect tense: 'av-' and
  'fais-'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.606305Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21702-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'être' has an irregular stem in the imperfect tense: 'ét-'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.606309Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21702-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'être', 'avoir' and 'faire' have regular endings in the imperfect tense: -ais, -ais,
  -ait, -ions, -iez, -aient."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.606313Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21702-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'il y avait' is the imperfect tense form of 'il y a', meaning 'there used to
  be'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.606317Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25549-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use the present to describe what you see on a photo, but use the future and
  conditional to develop the conversation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607598Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25549-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use time markers and other similarly useful structures to help organise longer
  responses using different tenses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607604Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25549-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Include regular and common irregular future and conditional verbs when writing about
  future plans."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607608Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21717-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Avoir' + noun is sometimes used to translate the English 'be' + adjective, e.g.
  'j'ai faim', 'j'aurai faim'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607948Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21717-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The simple future stem for the verb 'être' is 'ser-'. Regular future endings are
  added to this stem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607952Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21717-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The simple future stem for the verb 'avoir' is 'aur-'. Regular endings are added to
  this stem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607956Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21717-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[au] sounds like 'gauche'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607960Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25548-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The conditional has the same stem as the future tense for irregular verbs avoir,
  faire, aller and être."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607964Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25548-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """For the conditional of these verbs we add the imperfect endings to the irregular
  stems 'aur-', 'ser-', 'ir-' and 'fer-'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607968Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25548-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """J'aurais (I would have), j'irais (I would go), je serais (I would be) and je ferais
  (I would be) are key conditionals."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607972Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25548-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use the preposition 'en' when you want to say what type of vehicle you will use to
  travel."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607976Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25545-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The conditional can be used to say what someone would do or what would happen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607980Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25545-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The conditional endings are: -ais, -ais, -ait, -ions, -iez, -aient. These are the
  same as the imperfect."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607985Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25545-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The conditional is used in sentences with 'si' (if) and the imperfect to say what we
  would do if things were different."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.607989Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21704-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We use present tense for describing a photo, but a range of tenses, including
  imperfect, to extend the discussion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.608392Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21704-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use 'plus' and 'moins' followed by adjectives and 'plus de' and 'moins de' followed
  by nouns for contrasts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.608396Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21704-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Immediate repetition of a speaking task, with reduced support, improves
  performance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.608400Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21704-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It's important to plan to incorporate a range of past, present and future tenses
  when writing an extended text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.608404Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25542-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The conditional is a verb form that expresses the idea 'would'; it is often followed
  by a 2nd verb in the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.608408Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25542-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The conditional of -er verbs is formed by adding the imperfect tense endings to the
  infinitive stem, e.g. j'aimerais."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.608415Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25542-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The infinitive stem in the conditional and 1-verb future means that the sound [r],
  as in 'rue', is in all their forms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.608419Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25542-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """[a] as in ‘animal’ and [ai] as in 'vrai' are in the endings; 'je' future ending 'ai'
  is exceptionally pronounced [é]."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.608423Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25542-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use the conditional of 'vouloir' or 'aimer' + infinitive to say what you would
  'like' to do."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.608427Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21644-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Grouping vocabulary by word class is a useful strategy for deepening understanding
  of words and their role in sentences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.610010Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21644-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Direct object pronouns precede the verb. In negation, the direct object pronoun goes
  after ne and before the verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.610014Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21644-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Singular reflexive pronouns are me, te and se. They precede the verb."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.610019Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21644-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When translating, consider word order carefully, especially with direct object
  pronouns, reflexives and negation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.610024Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21644-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Direct object pronouns can be used to answer questions more efficiently, by avoiding
  repetition of the noun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.610030Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29148-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'Il est', 'il fait', 'il y a' and 'il faut' are common impersonal verbs."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.613717Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29148-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Impersonal verbs 'il vaut mieux' (it's better) and 'ça vaut la peine de' (it's
  worth) are followed by the infinitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.613721Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29148-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To talk about what you can, know, have to, or want to do, use modal verbs:
  'pouvoir', 'savoir', 'devoir', 'vouloir'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.613725Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29148-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "If modal verbs are followed by another verb, it must be in the infinitive form."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.613729Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29148-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The past participles of the four modal verbs are: 'dû', 'pu', 'voulu' and 'su'. They
  are used with 'avoir'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.613733Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29135-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Verbs which express a change of state, place or condition often use être as the
  auxiliary verb in the perfect tense."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.614482Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29135-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Past participles used with être must agree in gender and number with the subject of
  the verb."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.614486Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29135-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Tenses can be usefully combined to write/talk about people's past and current daily
  lives, achievements and events."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.614491Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29146-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Yes/no questions in all tenses are formed by inversion of subject and verb, adding
  'est-ce que' or using intonation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.615599Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29146-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To ask questions using question words, add a question word before the inverted verb
  or before 'est-ce que'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.615605Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29146-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Being able to ask questions in different tenses, as well as answer them, is key to
  successful communication."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.615609Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21635-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[ou] is pronounced like 'nous' and [u] is pronounced like 'tu'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618148Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21635-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """-ir verbs like ouvrir have the same present tense verb endings as regular
  -er verbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618152Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21635-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Four groups of -ir verbs are: verbs like choisir, verbs like partir, verbs like
  venir and verbs like ouvrir."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618156Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21635-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When using adjectives, it's important to know which ones precede and which follow
  the noun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618160Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21635-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Le château de Versailles is a palace near Paris built by Louis XIV, famous for the
  Hall of Mirrors and beautiful gardens"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618164Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25520-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Closed [eu] sounds like 'deux' or, when open or spelled [œu], sounds like
  'coeur'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618168Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25520-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An indirect object pronoun replaces the person, people or thing(s) that the verb
  action is done to."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618175Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25520-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The plural indirect object pronouns are: nous, vous, and leur."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618179Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25520-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Unlike direct object pronouns, indirect object pronouns don't change according to
  the gender of the nouns they replace."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.618183Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27600-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Même(s)', 'autre(s)', and 'quelque(s)', meaning 'same', 'other' and 'some', agree
  in number with the noun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.619071Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27600-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Tout le' meaning 'whole' or 'all' agrees in number and gender. 'Chaque' (each) and
  'plusieurs' (several) do not change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.619076Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27600-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """[c] is soft before e, i and y or if it has a cedilla [ç]: merci, ça va. Before all
  other letters, [c] is a hard sound."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.619080Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27600-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use demonstrative adjectives 'ce, cet, cette, ces' to mean 'this/that/those'; they
  often answer the question 'which?'"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.619084Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27600-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Use interrogative adjectives 'quel, quelle, quels, quelles' to ask 'which?'"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.619088Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21685-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To ask a question in the perfect tense, use inversion, intonation or est-ce que."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620758Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21685-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "t-liaison is common in inversion questions in the perfect tense: A-t-il gagné?"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620762Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21685-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Indefinite adjectives are used to describe a noun in a non-specific sense. They go
  before the noun they describe."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620766Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21685-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Même(s)', 'autre(s)', and 'quelque(s)', meaning 'same', 'other' and 'some', agree in
  number with the noun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620773Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21685-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Tout le' meaning 'whole' or 'all' agrees in number and gender. 'Chaque' (each) and
  'plusieurs' (several) do not change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.620777Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21677-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Comparative and superlative adverbs can be used to describe actions more
  precisely."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621139Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21677-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Known adjectives can be used in comparative or superlative sentences to make writing
  and speaking more complex."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621143Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21677-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Extended reading texts can be exploited to enrich our vocabulary and use of complex
  structures in familiar topics."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621147Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21677-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Immediate repetition of a speaking task, with reduced support, improves
  performance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.621151Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21690-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The verbs voir (to see), boire (to drink), croire (to believe) and faire (to do,
  make) are irregular in the present."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.622632Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21690-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The imperative is used to give instructions, commands or advice to one or more
  people."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.622636Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21690-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The imperative exists in the second person singular (tu), first person plural (nous)
  and second person plural (vous)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.622640Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21690-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[ai] sounds like 'vrai', [oi] sounds like 'voir' and [oy] sounds like envoyer."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.622647Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21631-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many -re verbs in the present tense follow the pattern of entendre: remove -re and
  add -s, -s, -, -ons, -ez, -ent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.622651Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21631-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some -re verbs follow the pattern of prendre: remove -dre in nous/vous/ils/elles
  forms and add -nent in ils/elles form."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.622655Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21631-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[en/an] sounds like 'enfant'. This is a common sound in -re verbs."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.622659Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21631-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """[e] sounds like 'je' but is lengthened to sound like [ê/è] in ils/elles form of
  verbs like prendre: ils prennent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.622663Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21631-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """-er verbs and -re verbs can be usefully combined to write/talk about my and others'
  daily activities."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.622668Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25537-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We can work out the meaning of new words if we recognise part of the word from a
  related word."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.622932Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25537-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Being able to apply word patterns, such as creating nouns from verb stems,
  significantly expands our vocabulary"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.622938Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25537-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Extend answers by justifying opinions and using a variety of adjectives, adverbs,
  pronouns and intensifiers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.622943Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21725-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are many cognates in this topic which can be used to infer meaning of
  surrounding words and understand context."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.632340Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21725-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Reading texts can be exploited to enrich our vocabulary on current issues."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.632344Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21725-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cognates may look very similar to English but sound quite different so attention
  must be paid to pronunciation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.632348Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21641-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[e] is pronounced liked 'je' and [é] is pronounced like 'écrire'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633163Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21641-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To say 'nothing', use ne...rien. The short form verb goes between the two parts in
  both single and two-verb structures."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633167Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21641-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To say 'no one', use ne...personne. The verb goes between ne and personne in
  single-verb structures: je n'aide personne."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633174Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21641-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In two-verb structures with 'ne ... personne', personne goes to the end, after both
  verbs: je ne vais dessiner personne."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633179Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25518-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are many 'Francophone' (French-speaking) countries to explore around the
  world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633369Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25518-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The prepositions à, de and en have many different functions and context must be used
  when translating into English."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633373Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-25518-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is helpful to reference Francophone countries whenever possible in writing and
  speaking."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633377Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21723-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'Ne ... que' means 'only'. 'Que' follows the verb and precedes the noun, e.g. 'il ne
  regarde que des films'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633384Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21723-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """For 'neither ... nor', 'ne' precedes the verb and each 'ni' precedes one of the
  negated qualities/nouns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633388Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21723-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "[-aill-/-ail] sounds like 'taille', [-ill-/-ille] sounds like 'fille'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.633393Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

